Title: Take Me Home

reviewText: WOW.  This film is one of the best films I've seen ever and the best film seen this year.  This film will connect with so many people on many different levels.  It is a great movie from the standpoint of romantic comedy or independent or drama or comedy:  It fits all of those genres and more.  Excellent writing and the characters are spot-on and you will find yourself reminiscing about your own relationships not only with your partner, but also with your family members.  The music is absolutely amazing, especially the music by Bootstraps (Fortyfive) and all I can say is this is a movie that I bought to keep forever because it is that wonderful.  Watch it and you will see that it will change your heart forever.  Congratulations to you, Sam Jaeger, for outstanding writing, directing, and acting and to Amber Jaeger for your sensitive and intuitive acting. To both of you, I will be looking forward to your next work. To anyone considering film work as an art, this movie will inspire you.  WONDERFUL, AMAZING, INSPIRING, MOVING FILM...THANK YOU.
Title: Take Me Home

Title: Take Me Home

reviewText: This is a classic comedy situation:  two people with clashing personalities get stuck together on a cross-country journey with a variety of delays and setbacks.  Why is this one so good?The plot is not particularly original, and the scenes are not incredibly original, creative or surprising. There are some holes in the plot--but they can be ignored well enough. However, the acting is fantastic and the characters are appealing--both the lead actors have great comedic timing. The little surprises in plot and dialogue are cute and funny. The characters are realistic and you like them both equally. The filming, editing, and music are done very well.We found ourselves chuckling out loud quite a bit during the movie, and when it ended, it left us feeling good and happy. We were quite surprised to see one of the scenes shot in a parking lot near our small town in SE Ohio. Small world! But we got a kick out of that!

reviewText: I can not express how thought-provoking this movie was, and it was done in such an artistic, delightful way.  Each scene, though seemingly unimportant on the surface, was artfully crafted, taking on greater meaning and speaking volumes as the movie travels onward.  Though the characters(who are opposites) appear to be running away from their lives, are really reconnecting with them: their pasts and their futures.  All at the same time. Together.  It was amazing.  This movie is HUGE.  I haven't seen anything like it in a very long time.  It's the kind of movie you can't stop thinking about after viewing it.  So, do not turn it off or you'll deprive yourselves of seeing each layer, more emotionally raw than the last one, peeled away.  And you'll realize that no one, on the surface, is really what they seem.  However, you'll feel satisfied by the end of it, because you'll know that each character will heal.  It is a truly amazing story to watch.  The acting was perfect!  Thank you to those who put their hearts and souls into it!  We marveled at it and enjoyed it immensely!  We will be watching it again and recommending it to all our friends!
summary: Best Movie I've Seen in a Long Time!!!*****

reviewText: I don't review things often unless I feel really compelled to. And this one compelled me. What a delightful film. The humor was on spot, but not heavy handed. The buildup of the relationship between these two was believable and I love how they handled themselves like adults would. I was bothered by one small scene in the beginning but the main character addresses it and apologizes for it later so I appreciated that. The leads have great chemistry which is probably partially due to them being married in real life, but (let's be honesty) at the same time we've all seen married couples have poor chemistry on screen too and so I think we can safely say their excellent acting played a big role too. I like road trip films/books/tropes and this one wasn't as predictable as I thought it was going to be. Sure there are a few expected tropes, but they were well done. This one was good enough for me to buy it to keep. It's one I can see lounging around and putting on during a lazy weekend. Highly recommended.

reviewText: I didn't like the movie at first...it seemed aimed at a  20-something audience.  The soundtrack underlined that impression.  Another road trip, I thought, with two characters with warring personalities  who will encounter troubles and eventually fall in love.  A tried and true formula.But somehow I stuck with it, probably because the actors were very good.  I really liked the angry young woman and then the shluppy cab driver warmed up to me.  There were some good stops along the way.  The guy's family in Boulder was perfect. I loved his uptight dad and his mom who kept saying "How Fun!"  Then, the girl's sweet eccentric mom in Las Vegas....a heartwarmer.  The scene at the memorial service was a little maudlin for me and the only scene that didn't ring true. The end was trite, too, but somehow, by that time I had forgiven them all.After I saw the film I learned that the lead actor, Sam Jaeger,also wrote and directed the film and his leading woman is his real-life wife, Amber.  It makes sense, as they had such perfect chemistry and the whole film had that warmth about it that comes from a labor of love. I'd like to seem them together again, maybe in something with a little more depth.PS.  A week later.  I just saw another "romantic road trip" film that I think is worthy of comparison to this one.  It's a French film, "As the Sea Rises" and in my opinion, is a much better film...much less formulaic and predictable...It has characters who don't look like movie stars and their lives are much more interesting and realistic.  I recommend it.

reviewText: Quick Overview: Claire receives the news her father has a heart attack and, hysterical, she hails a cab and tells the driver, "Drive." Thom, perhaps confused and maybe intrigued, complies. To his surprise, he winds up driving all the way from New York to California. On the long road trip they build a fast friendship and then some."Take Me Home" is a clean and innocent romantic comedy. I only noticed a couple stray curses. Other than that it is pretty family friendly.Amber Jaeger plays Claire, who is charged emotionally and somewhat stubborn. Thom, who is played by her real-life husband, Same Jaeger, seems like he is still trying to figure a few things out. He may have had a hard go at life too. Both are fun to watch and easy to like. Their banter is laughable and their connection, while not really passionate, is still obvious.

reviewText: Sam Jaeger writes, directs and stars in this romantic, and believable situation comedy, which is neither overblown nor timid while starring his own wife in the opposite lead role.  Scenery mixes with a definite palpable chemistry as these two take to the road for a trip that does not start with the happiest of farewells.Thom (Sam Jaeger) is struggling to pay his rent, falling behind so he has to make money quickly.  He decides to drive a cab while living in New York City although without proper licensing to drive it and carrying many of his possessions in his back seat.  Not having any other choice, he picks up a hopeful but desperate fare in Claire.Claire (Amber Jaeger), who is a high-power businesswoman, catches her husband at their home in an obviously questionable situation with another woman, who compliments her on the 'color of her bedroom' before leaving their home.  Within the same time frame, she receives a call to let her know that her father has had a heart attack and is hospitalized; just at about the same time it all hits the fan with her marriage.  This causes her to run out into the street and randomly grab a cab that just so happens to be Thom.  In a "Shut up and just drive" situation, it is go, and Go Now!  The eventual destination is Encinitas, CA, but as far as Claire is concerned, anywhere would be better than where she is at the moment.This is an easier, sometimes sarcastic, mix of a story, being more subtle than in your face as it gains momentum.  The action is slower paced and the humor comes at you at the same speed, though there are some definite laughs catching one right out loud.  The couple goes from one mishap to another in some gorgeous and well shown scenery (Jesse Feldman), from the Big City, to Middle America, and onward.  This is all scored with some original and snappy music by 'Bootstraps' all coming together very well for an enjoyable movie that I would absolutely watch again.
summary: "Did You Ever Notice How Really Lonely Men Have Large DVD Collections?" - Claire

reviewText: "Just drive, that's what you said, just drive." Thom (Jaeger) is down on his luck. He can't get a job and just got kicked out of his apartment. In order to make money he decides to pretend he's a cab driver. After a few fares Claire (Jaeger) hails him down. She is also having a bad day and tells him to drive. So he does. I have gotten in the habit of not watching previews before watching a movie so I don't have any preconceived notions going in. I watched the preview for this one and really thought it would be a little boring. This was anything but boring. This movie takes two proved formulas and puts them together. A romantic comedy mixed with a road movie. The acting was OK and the budget for this was not the best but it was a great movie that is better then a lot of the high budget movies. This movie is pretty predictable but sometimes it works and this is an example of that. I tend to like the movies with an ending that isn't always happy but every once in a while a movie like this comes along and it just has a calming feeling when it works out the way it should. Overall, a very satisfying movie that deserves to be watched. I liked it a lot. I give it a B+.
summary: A very satisfying movie that deserves to be seen by more people then it will. I really liked it and recommend it. I say B+
Title: Take Me Home
